22
00:02:21,620 --> 00:02:24,640
I can imagine you singing on Eurostar one day.

23
00:02:25,620 --> 00:02:29,610
All those screaming girls wishing you could sing just for them.

24
00:02:31,660 --> 00:02:33,820
You have such a beautiful voice.

25
00:02:33,820 --> 00:02:35,650
You can't keep it a secret.

26
00:02:35,860 --> 00:02:38,970
Why not? You keep secrets.

27
00:02:39,350 --> 00:02:40,850
I do?

28
00:02:41,480 --> 00:02:45,570
You said I couldn't talk about the doctor we went to.

29
00:02:47,450 --> 00:02:48,990
That's true.

30
00:02:49,340 --> 00:02:50,850
You mustn't.

31
00:02:50,850 --> 00:02:52,680
Especially to your father.

32
00:02:53,080 --> 00:02:54,940
It's our secret, okay?

33
00:02:55,190 --> 00:02:57,210
Please. Okay.

34
00:03:37,480 --> 00:03:40,740
Stop teaching my son to sing like a fucking queer.

35
00:03:41,370 --> 00:03:43,080
Anton, it's for school.

36
00:03:43,930 --> 00:03:46,240
Nobody tells me how to raise my son.

37
00:03:48,170 --> 00:03:50,530
- Don't touch her! - You love your mother, huh?

38
00:03:50,700 --> 00:03:52,550
You love her more than your father?

39
00:03:53,470 --> 00:03:55,390
You won't love her so much...

40
00:03:56,850 --> 00:03:58,930
when you know our little secret.

41
00:03:59,350 --> 00:04:00,700
You're drunk.

42
00:04:00,700 --> 00:04:03,240
You want to know who your mama is, huh?

43
00:04:03,880 --> 00:04:05,860
- Mama's boy? - Stop it!

44
00:04:05,860 --> 00:04:07,160
Stop it!

45
00:04:09,290 --> 00:04:11,070
That's my boy!

46
00:04:12,110 --> 00:04:15,890
I knew there was a man in there. A man like me.

47
00:04:18,640 --> 00:04:20,260
I know what I am.

48
00:04:21,240 --> 00:04:23,530
And I know what that makes you.

49
00:04:24,810 --> 00:04:28,410
And this cunt, she's more than your mother.

50
00:04:28,720 --> 00:04:31,140
No!

51
00:04:52,560 --> 00:04:54,030
We have to go.

52
00:04:56,730 --> 00:04:58,160
He'll find us.

53
00:04:58,950 --> 00:04:59,920
I'm going to fix--

54
00:04:59,920 --> 00:05:01,160
Fix it.

55
00:05:02,700 --> 00:05:04,700
This time, he's not coming after us.

56
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:15,100
We're getting out of here.

57
00:05:16,150 --> 00:05:19,930
Wolfgang... it's not worth it.

58
00:05:23,450 --> 00:05:25,090
I'm not worth it.

59
00:05:30,560 --> 00:05:32,240
Wolfgang.

60
00:05:33,290 --> 00:05:34,710
Can you hear me?

61
00:05:35,950 --> 00:05:37,400
Can you hear me?

62
00:05:40,050 --> 00:05:41,490
Wolfgang.

63
00:05:42,030 --> 00:05:43,660
Can you hear me?

64
00:05:48,070 --> 00:05:49,550
Thank God.

65
00:05:52,320 --> 00:05:53,800
Oh, thank God.

66
00:05:55,560 --> 00:05:58,930
Don't say anything. They're monitoring everything. Okay?

67
00:05:58,930 --> 00:06:02,560
Just follow me. Follow my voice.

68
00:06:05,020 --> 00:06:07,340
I have you. I have you.

69
00:06:09,640 --> 00:06:11,490
Do you know we have Whispers?

70
00:06:13,100 --> 00:06:16,040
We're going to use him to get you free. Okay?

71
00:06:16,240 --> 00:06:17,600
Don't.

72
00:06:18,570 --> 00:06:19,890
What?

73
00:06:20,120 --> 00:06:22,840
Because I'm-- I'm not worth it.

74
00:06:23,190 --> 00:06:25,040
Wolfgang, you are.

75
00:06:26,480 --> 00:06:28,000
You are.

76
00:06:28,930 --> 00:06:31,780
I know what love is because of you.

77
00:06:33,540 --> 00:06:35,360
I love you, Wolfgang.

78
00:06:37,380 --> 00:06:40,570
And I swear we're going to get you free.

79
00:06:53,990 --> 00:06:56,600
What happened? Was that Wolfgang?

80
00:06:56,830 --> 00:06:58,780
They have him on sedatives and on blockers

81
00:06:58,780 --> 00:07:01,310
so it was difficult to connect,

82
00:07:01,310 --> 00:07:03,400
but at least they aren't hurting him anymore.

83
00:07:05,530 --> 00:07:06,840
That's good.

84
00:07:07,410 --> 00:07:09,860
Will said they wouldn't as long as we have Whispers.

85
00:07:11,550 --> 00:07:15,090
I don't know how much longer I can wait until the exchange.

86
00:07:15,140 --> 00:07:16,430
I know.

87
00:07:17,480 --> 00:07:18,960
It'll be soon.

88
00:07:19,820 --> 00:07:22,290
But right now, we need more of the liquid blocker.

89
00:07:22,900 --> 00:07:24,720
Yes, of course.

90
00:07:26,030 --> 00:07:28,420
I'm running low on methatactogen trioxide.

91
00:07:28,420 --> 00:07:30,570
Nomi will have to forge another prescription.

92
00:07:30,750 --> 00:07:32,250
Already on it.

93
00:07:35,440 --> 00:07:36,880
It's cooked.

94
00:07:40,850 --> 00:07:42,550
This should last us through the week.

95
00:07:42,550 --> 00:07:44,900
I don't think we have a week. We have to go soon.

96
00:07:44,900 --> 00:07:46,150
How was the d'Orsay?

97
00:07:46,150 --> 00:07:47,990
Sadly, it didn't work out.

98
00:07:48,730 --> 00:07:53,330
- So right now, Will is talking to Riley? - And with Sun, Kala.

99
00:07:53,340 --> 00:07:55,900
Our exchange plan is based on finding the right location

100
00:07:55,900 --> 00:07:57,490
and disguisable transportation,

101
00:07:57,490 --> 00:07:59,530
and right now we have neither.

102
00:07:59,530 --> 00:08:01,570
Yeah, we go check it out!

103
00:08:02,350 --> 00:08:02,930
And now Capheus.

104
00:08:02,940 --> 00:08:05,630
Capheus? But I thought he was trying to buy a police van?

105
00:08:06,360 --> 00:08:07,830
Guess what I found?

106
00:08:11,960 --> 00:08:13,140
The van that should work.

107
00:08:13,140 --> 00:08:14,210
Great.

108
00:08:14,210 --> 00:08:15,600
A little paint.

109
00:08:16,860 --> 00:08:18,350
It'll be perfect.

110
00:08:19,370 --> 00:08:20,670
Okay.

111
00:08:21,280 --> 00:08:22,800
It's a start.

112
00:08:24,060 --> 00:08:26,240
Will, what just happened?

113
00:08:26,240 --> 00:08:27,850
Capheus found a van.

114
00:08:27,970 --> 00:08:30,750
So, Will just saw through Capheus' eyes?

115
00:08:31,180 --> 00:08:33,130
Sort of. It feels more like you're there

116
00:08:33,130 --> 00:08:34,660
than you're looking through their eyes.

117
00:08:34,660 --> 00:08:35,570
That is so freaking cool!

118
00:08:35,570 --> 00:08:37,850
I don't know if I'll get over it. It's mind-blowing.

119
00:08:37,860 --> 00:08:42,360
I can feel my ideas of self... expanding.

120
00:08:42,360 --> 00:08:43,860
Sometimes it's not great.

121
00:08:43,860 --> 00:08:47,240
You know we can hear you... even when you lower your voice.

122
00:08:47,240 --> 00:08:49,000
I didn't mean anything.

123
00:08:49,020 --> 00:08:51,150
- Who's that? - It's Nomi.

124
00:08:53,120 --> 00:08:55,450
Maybe Sans Jour is the best option?

125
00:08:55,680 --> 00:08:56,870
People know you've played there.

126
00:08:56,870 --> 00:08:59,080
They might be expecting it after Amsterdam,

127
00:08:59,080 --> 00:09:02,060
but we are running out of options.

128
00:09:06,230 --> 00:09:07,490
I need Whisper's shot.

129
00:09:07,490 --> 00:09:08,900
Kala.

130
00:09:09,850 --> 00:09:11,010
It's ready.

131
00:09:14,350 --> 00:09:15,700
And...

132
00:09:15,920 --> 00:09:17,480
I'm on my way.

133
00:09:18,800 --> 00:09:20,090
Wait for me.

134
00:09:23,540 --> 00:09:25,290
Is there anything else on Jonas' phone?

135
00:09:25,370 --> 00:09:26,990
Nothing. The only calls he made

136
00:09:26,990 --> 00:09:29,710
were to the Secretary, Peapod, and Just Eat.

137
00:09:29,710 --> 00:09:31,350
We need more on the Secretary.

139
00:09:31,350 --> 00:09:33,330
Right now, he's our only direct line to the Chairman.

140
00:09:33,330 --> 00:09:34,970
If we had better equipment...

141
00:09:34,970 --> 00:09:36,590
Still no word from Bug?

142
00:09:37,130 --> 00:09:39,770
No, but you know that's Bug.

143
00:09:42,730 --> 00:09:45,800
Actually, it isn't like Bug at all,

144
00:09:45,990 --> 00:09:47,440
but I don't want Neets to know

145
00:09:47,440 --> 00:09:49,880
that I am completely freaking out about it.

146
00:09:49,880 --> 00:09:51,730
BPO doesn't know he exists.

147
00:09:51,730 --> 00:09:54,200
Diego couldn't find the official documents on him anywhere.

148
00:09:54,200 --> 00:09:56,380
He's like a character from one of my movies.

149
00:09:56,450 --> 00:09:57,860
No, he's better.

150
00:09:57,860 --> 00:10:00,000
Because he's real.

151
00:10:00,850 --> 00:10:02,660
We have to stay focused.

152
00:10:02,830 --> 00:10:05,400
We know BPO's going to do everything they can to stop us,

153
00:10:05,400 --> 00:10:07,400
but as long as we stick to our plan--

154
00:10:07,400 --> 00:10:09,770
Holy shit! Now this is something.

155
00:10:09,770 --> 00:10:11,440
- What? - Elizabeth.

156
00:10:11,440 --> 00:10:13,560
- Who's Elizabeth? - Whisper's wife.

157
00:10:13,570 --> 00:10:16,260
I thought BPO moved her and their daughter to a safe house?

158
00:10:16,310 --> 00:10:17,710
There's no address listed.

159
00:10:17,710 --> 00:10:20,710
But it is good to know that even people under BPO's protection

160
00:10:20,710 --> 00:10:22,760
follow the same rules as the rest of us.

161
00:10:22,760 --> 00:10:24,790
When they file for divorce.

162
00:10:33,180 --> 00:10:37,050
Morning, Milt. On the stool.

163
00:10:39,110 --> 00:10:40,560
Look at my wall.

164
00:10:51,080 --> 00:10:52,510
How are you doing today?

165
00:10:54,410 --> 00:10:56,820
I know you don't want to answer my questions.

166
00:10:58,780 --> 00:11:00,240
You don't have to.

167
00:11:00,380 --> 00:11:03,140
Jonas pretty much told me everything I need to know.

168
00:11:07,280 --> 00:11:10,390
Yeah, we were just talking about you and your wife...

169
00:11:10,670 --> 00:11:12,060
Elizabeth.

170
00:11:13,100 --> 00:11:16,310
And Jonas really seemed to think that she loves you, but...

171
00:11:17,050 --> 00:11:18,460
I don't know.

172
00:11:26,640 --> 00:11:30,380
We were also talking about... your daughter.

173
00:11:32,150 --> 00:11:33,680
What was her name?

174
00:11:39,050 --> 00:11:40,590
Do you miss her?

175
00:11:41,410 --> 00:11:43,620
A typical father would, but...

176
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:46,790
you're not typical, are you?

177
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:51,750
See, I figure when someone cuts open the skull

178
00:11:51,750 --> 00:11:56,510
of a young girl like Sara Patrell while she's still alive...

179
00:11:58,360 --> 00:12:00,770
they can't possibly look at another little girl

180
00:12:00,770 --> 00:12:02,600
and not think about that.

181
00:12:03,900 --> 00:12:05,520
Maybe you can.

182
00:12:08,580 --> 00:12:11,460
As a boy, I was an exceptional student.

183
00:12:12,200 --> 00:12:13,710
I loved reading.

184
00:12:16,250 --> 00:12:21,100
I opened a book and found secrets and knowledge hidden inside.

185
00:12:23,220 --> 00:12:24,360
When I was a medical student,

186
00:12:24,360 --> 00:12:28,720
I learned how to operate on human beings.

187
00:12:29,850 --> 00:12:32,130
I imagined they had names and lives,

188
00:12:32,310 --> 00:12:34,630
but as far as I was concerned,

189
00:12:35,180 --> 00:12:37,460
they were the same as books...

190
00:12:38,630 --> 00:12:41,290
except I opened them with my knife.

191
00:12:42,720 --> 00:12:46,760
Every moment I remain here brings me closer to the moment

192
00:12:46,760 --> 00:12:51,620
I will open Ms. Gunnarsdottir while she is still alive

193
00:12:51,910 --> 00:12:57,570
so that you can feel as I slice into her cerebellum...

194
00:12:58,900 --> 00:13:03,480
and cut after cut, her secrets and knowledge

195
00:13:03,480 --> 00:13:06,050
will spill across my table.

196
00:13:11,530 --> 00:13:15,820
When all that remains of her and you and your cluster...

197
00:13:15,900 --> 00:13:19,840
are the measurements and observations in my notebook,

198
00:13:20,620 --> 00:13:22,200
I will go home...

199
00:13:23,540 --> 00:13:26,520
and I will kiss my beautiful wife and my daughter...

200
00:13:27,630 --> 00:13:30,880
and I will return to my exceptional life.

201
00:13:33,990 --> 00:13:36,650
I wouldn't be so sure about that, Milt.

202
00:13:38,140 --> 00:13:40,100
That beautiful wife of yours?

203
00:13:42,150 --> 00:13:44,680
She just filed for divorce.

204
00:13:49,450 --> 00:13:51,040
There's no going back.

205
00:13:52,510 --> 00:13:53,880
Not for you,

206
00:13:54,350 --> 00:13:55,690
not for me...

207
00:13:57,090 --> 00:13:58,540
not for any of us.

209
00:14:05,900 --> 00:14:07,670
That time again, Jonas.

210
00:14:08,850 --> 00:14:10,930
"The bonds that bind another person

211
00:14:10,930 --> 00:14:14,410
to ourself exist only in our mind."

212
00:14:16,270 --> 00:14:18,940
I wonder if Monsieur Proust was a sensate.

213
00:14:18,940 --> 00:14:21,740
I doubt he was ever handcuffed to a radiator.

214
00:14:22,480 --> 00:14:23,850
Here you go.

215
00:14:30,830 --> 00:14:33,170
I must compliment you on these blockers.

216
00:14:33,820 --> 00:14:36,180
Really top-shelf stuff.

217
00:14:36,180 --> 00:14:38,890
None of the nausea you get with regular homemade.

218
00:14:38,920 --> 00:14:40,310
Thank you.

219
00:14:45,220 --> 00:14:46,580
Still don't trust me?

220
00:14:46,580 --> 00:14:49,780
Give us a reason to trust you. Tell us about the Chairman.

221
00:14:50,040 --> 00:14:52,070
Now that sounds like Will talking.

222
00:14:52,160 --> 00:14:53,700
If he was using you as a watchdog...

223
00:14:53,710 --> 00:14:55,000
You must have talked to him.

224
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:59,790
I explained he uses a voice modulator. He wears a bio-mask.

225
00:14:59,790 --> 00:15:01,410
He's quite a paranoid fellow.

226
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:02,750
- So you say. - So you say.

227
00:15:02,750 --> 00:15:05,290
- Thing is, we want to trust you, Jonas. - You helped us once.

228
00:15:05,290 --> 00:15:07,350
What we can't figure out is why you stopped.

229
00:15:07,780 --> 00:15:08,720
It seems we keep returning

230
00:15:08,720 --> 00:15:10,980
to that moment you and I first met, Will,

231
00:15:10,980 --> 00:15:12,720
in the convenience store.

232
00:15:12,720 --> 00:15:17,220
I asked you to choose between what you heard and what you felt.

233
00:15:17,240 --> 00:15:19,980
You told me the choice you made was a mistake.

234
00:15:20,080 --> 00:15:22,640
No, the mistake is thinking we're back in the same place.

235
00:15:23,060 --> 00:15:24,500
We're not.

236
00:15:24,610 --> 00:15:27,250
You're a prisoner handcuffed to a radiator.

237
00:15:27,830 --> 00:15:29,250
So I am.

238
00:15:29,850 --> 00:15:31,580
Let's talk about Angelica.

239
00:15:32,310 --> 00:15:34,660
I'm trying to understand her decision to go to Chicago.

240
00:15:34,670 --> 00:15:37,070
She was there looking for her first cluster.

241
00:15:37,560 --> 00:15:40,800
And then she starts working with Kolovi and Whispers.

242
00:15:40,800 --> 00:15:43,300
And this is the part that bothers me.

243
00:15:43,300 --> 00:15:44,820
She helped build a machine

244
00:15:44,920 --> 00:15:48,360
that uses lobotomized sensates to murder people.

245
00:15:48,360 --> 00:15:49,690
That does not sound like the Angelica

246
00:15:49,690 --> 00:15:51,540
you described in the train station.

247
00:15:52,670 --> 00:15:53,920
In the ninth century,

248
00:15:53,920 --> 00:15:57,920
Chinese alchemists were searching for an elixir to prolong life.

249
00:15:59,220 --> 00:16:03,360
They combined saltpeter, sulfur, and charcoal...

250
00:16:04,230 --> 00:16:06,040
and gave the world gunpowder.

251
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:08,970
Come on, Jonas, stop bullshitting.

252
00:16:18,770 --> 00:16:20,280
Angelica.

253
00:16:25,220 --> 00:16:28,490
There is no one in the world I have known better.

254
00:16:32,560 --> 00:16:33,790
But I never could have imagined

255
00:16:33,790 --> 00:16:36,530
what she would do during her brief life.

256
00:16:49,020 --> 00:16:51,300
She left the cabin because she loved Raoul,

257
00:16:51,300 --> 00:16:54,880
and somehow she could feel he was alive in Chicago.

258
00:16:55,450 --> 00:16:57,040
Once she was there...

259
00:16:57,670 --> 00:17:01,030
she wanted to understand what Kolovi and Whispers were doing.

260
00:17:01,220 --> 00:17:03,140
She needed them to trust her.

261
00:17:18,050 --> 00:17:20,570
Very soon, she realized she could use their technology

262
00:17:20,580 --> 00:17:22,120
to build a machine to trace

263
00:17:22,120 --> 00:17:24,720
her psycellium connection to her children.

264
00:17:24,720 --> 00:17:26,050
She worked secretly,

265
00:17:26,050 --> 00:17:28,800
developing a graft of neural-morphic ligature

266
00:17:28,800 --> 00:17:32,620
and using the conductivity of psycellium to send a signal.

267
00:17:33,050 --> 00:17:37,120
Imagine a sonar that emits not sound...

268
00:17:38,900 --> 00:17:40,320
but pain.

269
00:17:44,850 --> 00:17:46,380
Pain, Will.

270
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:48,220
Pain connects us.

271
00:17:48,320 --> 00:17:52,350
Pain binds us better to one another than anything else.

272
00:18:12,680 --> 00:18:16,060
Oh, my baby. I'm so...

273
00:18:19,260 --> 00:18:20,620
Milton.

274
00:18:21,930 --> 00:18:24,680
I--

275
00:18:25,910 --> 00:18:28,140
I thought that you were going to laugh at me.

276
00:18:28,150 --> 00:18:32,300
I just... didn't really want to show you until I was certain,

277
00:18:32,300 --> 00:18:36,110
but now I am, I...

278
00:18:36,280 --> 00:18:38,600
Look. It's a breakthrough.

279
00:18:38,840 --> 00:18:41,020
I just followed your research.

280
00:18:44,060 --> 00:18:45,690
Extraordinary.

281
00:18:48,060 --> 00:18:49,400
Extraordinary.

282
00:18:54,410 --> 00:18:57,350
A Chicago cop can understand that life doesn't always allow us

283
00:18:57,350 --> 00:18:59,610
to be the best version of ourselves.

284
00:19:00,970 --> 00:19:03,190
Particularly when circumstances demand

285
00:19:03,190 --> 00:19:05,450
we lie and betray our friends...

286
00:19:05,910 --> 00:19:10,110
or compels us to handcuff an ally to a radiator.

287
00:19:22,630 --> 00:19:24,050
Neets?

288
00:19:31,640 --> 00:19:33,280
There you are.

289
00:19:45,100 --> 00:19:46,550
I couldn't sleep.

290
00:19:47,040 --> 00:19:48,530
Are you okay?

291
00:19:50,130 --> 00:19:54,190
Sometimes all this... it's hard.

292
00:19:55,220 --> 00:19:57,470
I mean, we're in Paris, Nom.

293
00:19:58,460 --> 00:20:00,340
That's the Eiffel Tower.

294
00:20:03,370 --> 00:20:04,520
When I was in college,

295
00:20:04,520 --> 00:20:07,640
all I thought about was coming to this city.

